## ðŸ§© Systemd & Service Management

| Command | Description |
|----------|--------------|
| `systemctl status` | Show overall systemd status |
| `systemctl list-units --type=service` | List active services |
| `systemctl list-unit-files --state=enabled` | Show enabled services |
| `systemctl start <service>` | Start a service immediately |
| `systemctl stop <service>` | Stop a running service |
| `systemctl restart <service>` | Restart a service |
| `systemctl reload <service>` | Reload service configuration (no restart) |
| `systemctl enable <service>` | Enable service to start on boot |
| `systemctl disable <service>` | Disable autostart for a service |
| `systemctl is-enabled <service>` | Check if a service starts on boot |
| `systemctl mask <service>` | Completely disable service (cannot start) |
| `systemctl unmask <service>` | Re-enable a masked service |
| `systemctl daemon-reload` | Reload unit files after editing them |
| `systemctl show <service>` | Display all properties of a service |
| `systemctl cat <service>` | Show service unit file definition |
| `systemctl edit --full <service>` | Edit the full unit file |
| `systemctl list-timers` | List all systemd timers (scheduled tasks) |
| `systemctl enable --now <service>` | Enable and start service immediately |
| `systemctl disable --now <service>` | Stop and disable service immediately |

---

### ðŸ§  Systemd Diagnostics & Boot Analysis

| Command | Description |
|----------|--------------|
| `systemctl --failed` | Show failed units |
| `journalctl -xe` | Show latest critical logs |
| `journalctl -u <service>` | View logs for a specific service |
| `journalctl -b` | Logs since last boot |
| `journalctl -b -1` | Logs from previous boot |
| `journalctl --disk-usage` | Show log storage usage |
| `systemd-analyze` | Show total boot time |
| `systemd-analyze blame` | List services by startup time |
| `systemd-analyze critical-chain` | Display dependency boot order |
| `loginctl list-sessions` | Show active user sessions |
| `loginctl show-session <id>` | Inspect a specific session |
| `hostnamectl` | View or change hostname and system info |
| `localectl` | View or change system locale and keymap |
| `timedatectl` | Manage system time, date, and NTP sync |

---

### ðŸ§± Writing & Managing Custom Unit Files

| Command | Description |
|----------|--------------|
| `/etc/systemd/system/<name>.service` | System-wide custom service |
| `~/.config/systemd/user/<name>.service` | Per-user service unit |
| Example minimal unit: |
| ```ini
  [Unit]
  Description=My Custom Service
  After=network.target

  [Service]
  ExecStart=/usr/bin/mycommand --option
  Restart=always

  [Install]
  WantedBy=multi-user.target
  ``` |
| `systemctl daemon-reload` | Reload unit files after creation/edit |
| `systemctl enable --now myservice.service` | Enable and start custom service |
| `systemctl status myservice.service` | Check its current state |

---

### ðŸ§© Systemd Timer Examples

| Command | Description |
|----------|--------------|
| `systemctl list-timers --all` | List all timers (active & inactive) |
| `/etc/systemd/system/backup.timer` | Timer unit definition |
| ```ini
  [Unit]
  Description=Run Backup Daily

  [Timer]
  OnCalendar=daily
  Persistent=true

  [Install]
  WantedBy=timers.target
  ``` |
| `/etc/systemd/system/backup.service` | Service triggered by timer |
| ```ini
  [Unit]
  Description=Daily Backup

  [Service]
  Type=oneshot
  ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/backup.sh
  ``` |
| `systemctl enable --now backup.timer` | Start and enable the timer |

---

ðŸ’¡ **Pro Tips:**
- Use `systemd-analyze verify <unitfile>` to check syntax and dependencies.  
- `journalctl -fu <service>` follows logs live (like `tail -f`).  
- Per-user systemd units run via `systemctl --user`.

